        </div>

        <div class="border-b border-aiq-border pb-aiq-xl">
          <h3 class="font-serif text-aiq-xl font-normal tracking-aiq-tight text-aiq-fg-primary mb-aiq-sm mt-0">Is HackerEarth India-focused?</h3>
          <p class="font-sans text-aiq-md text-aiq-fg-secondary leading-relaxed m-0">
            Yes — HackerEarth is headquartered in Bengaluru and has strong India roots, with active developer communities across Indian cities. Its enterprise hiring platform is used globally. AssessIQ is similarly India-first, with calibrated question packs for Indian IT role stacks, local data residency, and pricing designed for Indian team budgets.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="border-b border-aiq-border pb-aiq-xl">
          <h3 class="font-serif text-aiq-xl font-normal tracking-aiq-tight text-aiq-fg-primary mb-aiq-sm mt-0">Which is better for coding tests — HackerEarth or AssessIQ?</h3>
          <p class="font-sans text-aiq-md text-aiq-fg-secondary leading-relaxed m-0">
            Both platforms support live coding tests with test-case execution. HackerEarth's question library is larger (36,000+ questions, 40+ languages) and its community-sourcing tools are a genuine differentiator. AssessIQ's coding tests are paired with structured rubric scoring — the admin sees test-case pass rates, submitted code, and a rationale band — making results easier to defend in a structured hiring process.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3 class="font-serif text-aiq-xl font-normal tracking-aiq-tight text-aiq-fg-primary mb-aiq-sm mt-0">When should I choose AssessIQ over HackerEarth?</h3>
          <p class="font-sans text-aiq-md text-aiq-fg-secondary leading-relaxed m-0">
            AssessIQ is likely a better fit if: (a) you want private, branded assessments without exposing your hiring pipeline to a public developer community; (b) structured scoring with per-answer rationale matters for your review process; or (c) you need bulk hiring assessments across multiple roles without paying for community or hackathon features you won't use.
          </p>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

